##Clinical trial results: Chinese study confirmed that Kleenex had little effect on severe mortality

On March 19, the Chinese team's study of the anti-aids drug The New England Journal of Medicine Ritonavir was published online in the journal Nejm, lopinavir and Ritonavir did not show any improvement in clinical outcomes or reduction in mortality in patients with severe new coronary disease. Ritonavir, or cleats, is an HIV Protease inhibitor.

The study showed that the Ritonavir benefit was minimal, bringing forward the median time for clinical improvement by just one day to 15 days, compared with 16 days in the control group.

According to the The New England Journal of Medicine, this is the first time since the outbreak that the world's top medical journal has published the results of a clinical trial to treat the new coronavirus, it is one of only a handful of drug trials published during Emerging Infectious Diseases of the epidemic, including SARS.

The main authors were from china-japan Friendship Hospital, National Respiratory Disease Clinical Research Center and Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. The authors were Cao Bin, Wang Chen, and Zhang Dingyu of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, a Chinese and Japanese hospital.

A few high-quality clinical trials

The study was designed as a prospective, randomized, standard-treatment-controlled, open-label clinical trial (RCT) . The study was not double-blind and did not limit the time between onset and group entry.

The study randomly assigned patients on a 1:1 scale. The Control Group, 100 patients, received standard treatment according to the latest edition of the COVID-19 issued by the NHC; the Lopinavir Litteau Group, 99 patients, received standard treatment, increase the Lopinavir Ritonavir treatment. For the latter regimen, Lopinavir 400 MG Ritonavir 100 MG twice daily for 14 days.

The primary end point for evaluation was the time to clinical improvement. The LOPINAVIR Litteau Group of clinical studies used a 7 point composite endpoint index. The end point for clinical improvement is the end point recommended by the WHO expert group on the development blueprint. The 7-point scale includes the following grades: 1. Not Hospitalized, and can continue to engage in daily activities; 2. Not Hospitalized but unable to continue daily activities; 3. Hospitalization without oxygen. 4. Hospitalization, need oxygen; 5. Hospitalization requires Nasal high-flow oxygen therapy, noninvasive mechanical ventilation, or both; 6. Hospitalization requires ECMO, invasive mechanical ventilation, or both; 7. Death.

Of the 99 patients assigned to the Lopinavir Litteau group, 94(94.9%) received the assigned treatment, and 5 patients did not receive Lopinavir Ritonavir, in three cases, the cause was early death within 24 hours after randomization, and in two cases, the attending physician refused to prescribe Ritonavir after randomization.

Figure | time between the intention to treat population and clinical improvement: number at risk on the horizontal axis and cumulative improvement rate on the vertical axis. (Source: The New England Journal of Medicine)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The study found no improvement in clinical outcomes or reduction in mortality in the Ropinavir Litteau group compared to conventional supportive care in critically ill patients with new coronary disease.

The median time to clinical improvement between the two groups was 15 days in the Lopinavir Litteau group and 16 days in the control group, in the analysis of improved intention to treat excluding 3 early death patients. The differences were small but statistically significant, the study found.

In contrast to conventional support alone, the study did not find that adding Lopinavir Ritonavir reduced viral RNA load or reduced the time it took to detect viral RNA.

As for safety, there were 51 patients with serious adverse events: 19 in the Lopinavir Litteau group and 32 in the control group. The ROPINAVIR Litteau group had four major gastrointestinal adverse events, while the control group had no major gastrointestinal adverse events; the researchers determined that all four events were associated with the experimental drug. The incidence of respiratory failure, acute renal injury and secondary infection in the control group was higher than that in the Lopinavir Litteau group.

Thirteen (nearly 14%) of the patients receiving Lopinavir Ritonavir did not complete the 14 day course, the main causes were gastrointestinal adverse events such as Anorexia, nausea, abdominal discomfort or diarrhea and two serious adverse events (both acute gastritis) .

Research of high concern to WHO

According to Cao Bin, Lopinavir Ritonavir is listed by the WHO as one of the drugs to be evaluated in the Global R & D blueprint for a new coronavirus. The W.H.O. is paying close attention to the research and has called Cao Bin several times to ask about the main findings.

The Department of Science and education organized by the National Health Commission has highly affirmed the significance of this clinical trial, which provides a direct basis for the clinical treatment of new severe coronary disease.

Previous studies have shown that Lopinavir inhibits the human SARS virus in vitro, and the combination of Ritonavir and Lopinavir prolongs the plasma half life of Lopinavir by inhibiting cytochrome P450. An Open label study published in 2004 suggested that Ribavirin plus Lopinavir Ritonavir reduced the risk of adverse clinical outcomes and viral load in SARS patients. But the study was not randomized, did not have a control group, and used a combination of glucocorticoid and Ribavirin, making it difficult to assess the effect of Lopinavir Ritonavir.

Lopinavir has been shown to be active against the respiratory system coronavirus (MERS-CoV) in vitro and in animal models, and case reports have suggested that Lopinavir Ritonavir, in combination with Ribavirin and Interferon, can eliminate the virus, to keep the patient alive.

In view of the above background, the researchers registered with the China Clinical Trial Registry on Jan. 23 for a randomized, open, controlled study evaluating the efficacy and safety of Lopinavir and Ritonavir in the treatment of 2019 hospitalized patients with COVID-19 COVID-19 infection.

In fact, the registration time was already the first patient in the group, the first patient was officially randomized on January 18. Cao Bin explained that when the trial was completed on January 9, it was supposed to be registered with the Clinicaltrials.gov  , but the website refused to register it on the grounds that "the new coronavirus infection is endemic" .

Cao Bin described the process in detail on a live show: We looked at about 20 cases before starting the RCT study, and some doctors reported that the drug worked! But this is an isolated case, which means there's only twenty. The Lopiravir Ritonavir story is also known, and was once touted as a "Miracle Cure, " but that was after we launched the RCT. In the early days, even when we first looked at more than 20 cases, and some of the doctors said it worked, we didn't dare say, "This drug might be effective. ". We started the RCT study very rigorously and patiently, and our first patient was admitted on January 18, a week or so from January 9 through the ethics committee to January 18, we followed more than 20 patients in succession, but did not initiate a randomized study. We officially started the randomized study on January 18,2020, which is a starting point for our clinical study of Litteau.

The story, billed as a "miracle drug, " is the case of Peking University First Hospital and Wang Guangfa, the chief of critical care medicine. According to Wang, it took only a day for her body temperature to drop after taking Ritonavir.

"When you sharpen your knife, you cut your wood. "

Cao Bin, in the popular Wechat Account Nejm Medical Frontier, calls for a knife to be sharpened and a knife to be cut. Instead of carrying out one-arm observational studies to obtain inaccurate results, he wastes the energy of researchers and valuable resources of subjects, it is better to carry out randomized controlled clinical trials to test the efficacy and safety of several drugs in order to make China and even the world more relaxed in dealing with new emergent respiratory infectious diseases in the future.

There are many difficulties in treating newly emergent respiratory infectious diseases with fast, clear and effective drugs. SARS first broke out in China in 2003, but "we missed the search for a coronavirus treatment because of the limited conditions and research capabilities, " Cao Bin said. In his view, in the face of a new outbreak of respiratory infectious diseases, the window of exploration for effective treatment is extremely narrow and the most valuable resources need to be focused on prioritizing the evaluation of several drugs with full potential.

The Hong Kong, China based Ritonavir study is inconclusive, while the MERS study in patients infected with Mers in Saudi Arabia started late and has yet to be enrolled in a clinical trial, missed the opportunity to prove the efficacy and safety of Ritonavir.

It was the missed opportunity to test the drug twice in a row that led to a lack of definitive antiviral drug during the new crown outbreak. Cao Bin said the Wuhan findings not only provide a relatively clear clinical benefit to Ropinavir Ritonavir for severe antiviral drug pneumonia, but also provide valuable lessons for future exploration.

Interferon was not used in this study. Cao Bin told the live program that when he studied more than 20 cases before randomization, he found that inhaling interferon significantly increased the workload of the nurses in the isolation ward and increased the risk of producing aerosols, some patients observed in the inhalation of Interferon Airway response is larger, the emergence of Airway irritation of the adverse reactions.

Although the study did not provide a placebo control, Cao Bin said the GCP, which is responsible for managing drug clinical trials, was unable to distinguish between the Lopinavir Litteau group and the Control Group when conducting clinical end point evaluations.

The study was strictly randomized, Cao Bin said. The median age of both groups was 58 years, sex ratio, underlying diseases, laboratory tests at the time of enrollment, and the severity of these patients'conditions, as well as the intervention drugs (including hormones) used by these patients after enrollment, and they're all a match. In this context, the only difference between the two groups is that one group has "Lopiravir Ritonavir, " which "we can compare with confidence. ".

The researchers decided to continue with the study, which initially included a total of 160 patients, after deciding that the trial had insufficient statistical power.

Referring to the limitations of the study, the paper points out that the trial did not use the blind method, so doctors and patients who knew about the grouping might influence clinical decision making, which might influence the 7-point scale used in the study.

As to why he didn't go double blind, he told Deeptech that he had only Ritonavir on hand at the time and had no time to administer a placebo in order to advance the study.
